Both pods show the env var set correctly with your exact flag string, on both the transaction and payment services. Step 1 of the verification passes.

That confirms the env var is *present*, but not yet that the JVM actually *ingested* it. Run the step 2 check next — the JVM prints a confirmation line to stderr at startup when it reads the var:

```bash
oc logs txn-transactionservice-7965b65db-h7ql9 -n perf-transaction | grep "Picked up JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS"
```

Expected:
```
Picked up JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS: -XX:+UseG1GC -XX:+AlwaysPreTouch -XX:MaxRAMPercentage=80.0
```

If you see that line, you have hard proof the JVM applied the flags. If the log has rotated and you don't see it (long-running pod), confirm directly against the live JVM instead:

```bash
oc exec txn-transactionservice-7965b65db-h7ql9 -n perf-transaction -- jcmd 1 VM.flags | tr ' ' '\n' | grep -E "G1GC|AlwaysPreTouch|MaxRAMPercentage"
```

And to confirm the heap actually resolved to 80% of the pod's memory limit:

```bash
oc exec txn-transactionservice-7965b65db-h7ql9 -n perf-transaction -- java -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal -version | grep -i maxheapsize
```

Cross-check `MaxHeapSize` against 80% of the Deployment's `resources.limits.memory`. If it doesn't line up, the memory limit likely isn't set and the percentage is resolving against node RAM instead.

The env var being identical across both services also tells you the Helm change is consistent across your charts, which is what you want.
